up to speed on basic knowledge terms that can be very confusing to someone starting off.

00:23:17.439 --> 00:23:19.280
Yeah, the Institute is a very good resource.

00:23:22.479 --> 00:23:26.000
Awesome. Yeah, thank you so much. You know, I sit in these meetings with our product partners

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:30.560
and they're so smart and they have this whole like dictionary in their heads. And so they're

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:34.640
rattling things off and I get lost. So this is very helpful. Thank you.

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:44.640
Great, thank you. Okay, I see an earlier question you had asked,

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:48.319
Bill. I'm not sure if you're able to unmute. Do you want me to read it?

00:23:51.599 --> 00:23:58.719
The question was, Brian, are your colleagues and peers working on local laptops or perhaps

00:23:58.719 --> 00:24:05.920
on an on-prem larger system? And the follow-up question is, would your typical actuary need to

00:24:05.920 --> 00:24:12.560
install and manage RStudio or Anaconda on their own machine? What does the setup look like for them?

00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:21.920
Typically it's going to be, well, I'll describe my setup, which is probably typical these days,

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:32.160
2021, 23, 2023. I have a laptop. I work remotely. So I've got a laptop, which will

00:24:33.439 --> 00:24:42.160
refresh to your corporation server. We're an office, sorry, Microsoft shop,

00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:46.959
which means that we've got one drive. And so everything is cloud synced.

00:24:47.199 --> 00:24:56.959
And I think that's fairly typical. I have R installed. I'm not using RStudio server,

00:24:56.959 --> 00:25:01.599
although Rachel, everybody ought to. It's a really good product. I have used it. I know

00:25:01.599 --> 00:25:06.079
the Hartford does. I did some consulting for the Hartford and they had it. And it was a fantastic

00:25:06.079 --> 00:25:13.520
experience. The installation of R and RStudio is pretty straightforward. It used to be a lot more

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:24.640
painful, but I find that it's pretty smooth these days. So installing locally, my use of R

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:31.199
professionally has been largely on my own. The collaboration has usually been between me and

00:25:31.199 --> 00:25:38.000
someone at another company. And their GitHub will be the way that we're collaborating. Ideally,

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:44.160
that's my favorite way to collaborate, or we'll get lazy and use something like SharePoint or

00:25:44.160 --> 00:25:53.520
just email, forgive me. But those are easy ways to collaborate. Did I hit all of that? Anaconda,

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:59.680
not actually a big fan of Anaconda. It's really opinionated. And I find that whenever I install

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:03.920
it, I'll wind up with somehow three or four different flavors of Python on my device.

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:08.880
I'm probably doing something wrong. It's probably my fault. But I usually just install Python.

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:17.439
And as with R, it's usually pretty straightforward. If I were working with a team of actuaries for an

00:26:17.439 --> 00:26:22.479
insurance company, that's not my situation right now. I'm one of only a few actuaries. But if I

00:26:22.479 --> 00:26:27.280
were working with a team or managing a team, I would do something like RStudio server.

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:36.400
I don't want to sound like a shill composite, although I would love to. I know that Microsoft

00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:41.439
and others have similar cloud-based solutions that would probably work very, very well.

00:26:46.160 --> 00:26:52.400
Thank you. Another anonymous question was, when you say that actuary statistical analysis are

00:26:52.400 --> 00:26:58.800
similar to longitudinal analysis, does that include survival analysis sometimes?

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:10.800
Yes. There are globally two different flavors of actuary. There's a life insurance actuary,

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:17.920
and then there's every other actuary. In the US, it's life and health insurance. Outside of the US,

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:22.959
there's public health insurance schemes. And so actuaries, there's not a demand for it.

00:27:22.959 --> 00:27:29.280
But a life insurance actuary would absolutely use survival analysis. I think a lot of techniques

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:34.319
that are in survival—I'm not a life insurance actuary, so I'm talking out of school a little

00:27:34.319 --> 00:27:38.640
bit. But I think there are a lot of techniques in survival analysis that have their origin

00:27:39.199 --> 00:27:46.160
in human mortality studies. So yeah, survival analysis is a thing.

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:51.920
I wrote a paper about using survival analysis in loss observing, so you could kind of think

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:56.479
of that as a hybrid survival analysis and longitudinal analysis.

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:02.880
I didn't Google that paper fast enough in time there.

00:28:05.040 --> 00:28:07.040
There are better resources out there, yeah.

00:28:07.839 --> 00:28:15.920
So, okay, maybe taking a step back from some of the insurance topics. I know you said

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:20.560
that you do a lot of public speaking, and that's something that has come up as a question before

00:28:20.560 --> 00:28:26.479
here in the Hangout. Do you have any tips for us who are trying to get better at public speaking?

00:28:30.880 --> 00:28:40.800
I think finding a friendly room is not a bad place to start. So locally, here in Research

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:46.079
Triangle, North Carolina, there are not very many actuaries, but I think folks realize that

00:28:46.079 --> 00:28:50.479
this is a really good spot to be if you're into data science or statistics. We've got

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:56.079
the Research Triangle Park, we've got the universities, and we've got SAS here. So there

00:28:56.079 --> 00:29:04.800
is a very active and super-friendly community of data scientists. I'm very much involved with a

00:29:04.800 --> 00:29:13.040
meetup group of Research Triangle analysts, and we have monthly meetings. People can give talks

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:20.000
there. Really friendly room. That's not a bad place to start. What else could I say?

00:29:21.520 --> 00:29:26.400
Yeah, present to your family, present to your friends. That's another way to find a friendly

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:32.560
room. And then finally, just keep doing it. The first time that I ever spoke at an actuarial

00:29:32.560 --> 00:29:43.839
conference, I was so nervous. I thought that I was going to have a heart attack. I couldn't

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:52.719
believe just how petrified I was. But that was like 13, 14 years ago. It gets easier.

00:29:55.599 --> 00:30:00.079
I love that tip of just reaching out to different meetups groups and speaking

00:30:00.880 --> 00:30:06.400
there too. And I wanted to call out that Abigail just put in the chat, because we were talking a

00:30:06.400 --> 00:30:12.079
little bit earlier about this on LinkedIn, but she was looking for lightning talks for a DC

00:30:12.079 --> 00:30:17.680
meetup. So if anybody else organizes meetups and have links you want to share in the chat,

00:30:17.680 --> 00:30:25.040
that would be great too. Yeah, pretty much any major area is going to have them. I've not managed

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:30.319
to get to any of the DC meetups, but DC area is kind of where home office is. So when I'm

00:30:31.119 --> 00:30:37.439
going to the CAS office, it's in DC and I keep trying to catch up with the DC folks. But if

00:30:37.439 --> 00:30:43.119
you're in Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia, there's going to be a data nerd meetup in your town.

00:30:45.599 --> 00:30:52.400
I can vouch for Boston. That's our group. I see, Bill, you had another question in the chat. I'll

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:57.599
read it here. But Bill said, I'm always interested in security and regulatory issues. Do you

00:30:57.599 --> 00:31:03.439
anonymize or make up fake data? If so, what packages or methods do you use?

00:31:06.319 --> 00:31:14.160
In the insurance space, there is a need for publicly available data sets for research.

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:19.760
As you can guess, there are a lot of privacy issues that would make people uncomfortable.

00:31:19.760 --> 00:31:23.839
Companies certainly and policyholders are very uncomfortable sharing that data.

00:31:23.839 --> 00:31:30.719
There are a few kind of toy data sets out there, but we do simulate data for research purposes

00:31:30.719 --> 00:31:38.239
from time to time. When I'm researching, well, two things. One, again, for that

00:31:39.839 --> 00:31:45.760
reserve data, the longitudinal-ish data, there are several packages that will do that. There are

00:31:45.760 --> 00:31:51.439
about four or five. If you're not an expert, you've never heard of these things, but that will

00:31:51.439 --> 00:31:58.719
simulate these kinds of financial transactions. Beyond that, fairly straightforward, the

00:32:00.479 --> 00:32:06.800
ability to randomly generate a number in R, it's one of those really bedrock things

00:32:07.599 --> 00:32:14.479
that I really enjoyed when I first started using R. In Excel, I can remember I wanted

00:32:14.479 --> 00:32:20.880
to simulate something from a Poisson distribution. At that time, probably still today, there's no

00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:28.160
easy way to simulate Poisson, which is a very, very common thing in actuarial applications.

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:32.560
You couldn't do it. I'm reading numerical recipes and all these other crazy things.

00:32:34.479 --> 00:32:39.680
Maybe I could have just inverted the cumulative function, but whatever. In R,

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:46.239
I don't even need to do any of that. It's just R plus, and I've got 10,000 observations.

00:32:47.199 --> 00:32:52.719
Things like that. You can stack them. If you've got a cascading process,

00:32:53.680 --> 00:32:58.000
sort of a hierarchical simulation, pretty straightforward to do in R.

00:32:59.040 --> 00:33:06.880
My favorite way to tackle that is I'm a very data frame-centric programmer. I've got a data frame

00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:13.760
where I've got maybe 1,000 scenarios that have different parameters, and then just go row by row

00:33:13.760 --> 00:33:20.000
using per or something like that. Each row in a data frame becomes a new data frame that is

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:27.359
simulating a scenario. I can just easily nest and unnest and summarize all of that stuff.

00:33:28.880 --> 00:33:32.640
It's that Lego-based approach to simulation.

00:33:33.199 --> 00:33:38.800
Great. Thank you. Maybe this is a question for everybody on the call here, too,

00:33:38.800 --> 00:33:42.800
if you want to share links in the chat. Gaurav, do you want to jump in here?

00:33:47.199 --> 00:33:53.920
The question was, are there publicly available datasets for casualty insurance?

00:33:54.079 --> 00:33:58.880
I could have name-checked a few there. There's the insurance data package in R.

00:34:00.959 --> 00:34:05.520
Okay. Yeah, and there's another one that's not on CRAN because it's pretty massive.

00:34:08.320 --> 00:34:11.439
I'll dig up a link to that. Yeah, you can send it to me.

00:34:11.439 --> 00:34:17.600
I'll send it to you, too. Yeah. I'll try and make notes of where to follow up.

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:21.360
Javier, I see you had a question in the chat, too. Do you want to jump in here next?

00:34:24.479 --> 00:34:31.520
Thanks, Rachel. Yeah, thanks, Brian. I'm really enjoying your discussion here. I work with a ton

00:34:31.520 --> 00:34:37.280
of actuaries. I'm not an actuary myself, but I work at a healthcare insurance company. I'm in our

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:42.080
data science center of excellence, and a lot of our stakeholders are actuaries.

00:34:42.399 --> 00:34:51.040
We've had a lot of interest recently trying to get what feels kind of like a small army of Power

00:34:51.040 --> 00:35:03.199
BI devs to tap into more Python and R-related capabilities to work in conjunction with Power

00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:09.520
BI. I have a ton of Excel experience. I've got zero functional Power BI experience, so

00:35:10.959 --> 00:35:18.239
outside of clicking around the Power BI system, I know very little about it. I didn't know if you

00:35:18.239 --> 00:35:29.120
had any experience either pushing data or tables directly from Power BI to Power BI. I don't know

00:35:30.080 --> 00:35:36.080
either pushing data or tables directly from an RStudio IDE to Cloud Power BI,

00:35:36.800 --> 00:35:44.560
or maybe using Connect to facilitate that transfer. I'm still very much in exploratory mode,

00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:49.120
but I didn't know if you had any suggestions there. I'm going to have to defer to the rest

00:35:49.120 --> 00:35:55.600
of the folks. My experience with Power BI and Tableau, those two platforms, is virtually nil.

00:35:56.560 --> 00:36:05.600
My hypothesis is that if you're using Power BI or Tableau, you can source data probably from

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:14.080
a relational database or a CSV file. I probably have a workflow where I'm routinely populating

00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:20.639
data that I could then visualize. I may be off base there, but if someone said,

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:26.479
hey, you've got to use Power BI tomorrow, that's an approach that I would assume that I could take.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:36.399
I can't go without saying to check out the Connect, PositConnect docs that Connor shared

00:36:36.399 --> 00:36:42.719
there too. Javier, it looks like you have a meeting with the team tomorrow, so perfect timing

00:36:42.719 --> 00:36:51.840
to chat about that too. Cool. Okay, another anonymous question on Slido was, do you see

00:36:51.840 --> 00:36:58.639
R Markdown or Quarto's publishing functionality used in actuary stats work? For example,

00:36:58.639 --> 00:37:04.639
publishing your notebooks into tables, docs, or slides directly? Not as often as I would like.

00:37:05.360 --> 00:37:12.399
I am a big, big fan of R Markdown slash Quarto. I'm a little bit late to the party on Quarto.

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:19.120
I use it. The differences between Quarto and R Markdown, I'm still learning, so I use the terms

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:27.520
interchangeably. I wrote a 600-page textbook using R Markdown. I do pretty much all of my work

00:37:27.520 --> 00:37:36.080
in R Markdown. I find that I'm writing notes and long-form comments suddenly become the most

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:42.959
important bit in the document, and so it just becomes easy to have R Markdown slash Quarto

00:37:42.959 --> 00:37:52.159
as my starting point for work. Professionally, I've used it a lot. Stakeholders very often will

00:37:52.159 --> 00:37:58.399
want, this isn't all that they want, but very often they can be satisfied with a reasonably

00:37:58.399 --> 00:38:04.560
concise and informative Word document, or PDF if you'd rather, but giving them a Word document,

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:09.199
like, okay, here you go. Here are the tables, and here are the graphs, and here's the executive

00:38:09.199 --> 00:38:15.840
summary. I think that's a great way to share information. Actuaries are not using it as much.

00:38:15.840 --> 00:38:23.439
I think there's not as much awareness of R Markdown. I think the initial presumption is

00:38:23.439 --> 00:38:30.080
that R's greatest strength, or only strength rather, is in calculation. It can absolutely

00:38:30.080 --> 00:38:36.000
do that. It's got an incredible library of statistical and machine learning functionality,

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:44.479
but it does a lot more than that. That is slowly changing as with adoption of R generally.

00:38:45.679 --> 00:38:52.639
I see that as being a real big selling point when people find out that they can replace a very

00:38:52.639 --> 00:39:00.479
typical actuarial and kind of analytic workflow where I create a plot in Excel, and I have to

00:39:00.479 --> 00:39:06.719
copy and paste it into Word. That's operationally inefficient. It's operationally dangerous.

00:39:07.840 --> 00:39:16.719
So the notion that my entire analytics report is in one file, all of the code, all of the narrative,

00:39:16.719 --> 00:39:22.479
all of the tables, it's like telling me that I can breathe underwater and fly.

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:30.320
It's really fantastic. So I think that as actuaries become aware of that capability,

00:39:30.320 --> 00:39:36.159
they will get pretty happy about it, as will people who need to communicate with actuaries.

00:39:38.719 --> 00:39:43.120
I like the way you put that copying and pasting is operationally dangerous.

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:50.879
Yeah. I'm not the only actuary who has been burned by that. Where you're in a meeting,

00:39:50.879 --> 00:39:55.679
everyone's looking at the same file, and the plot didn't update.

00:39:56.479 --> 00:40:01.040
What do you mean we're losing $1 billion a day? Oh, sorry, that's yesterday's graph.

00:40:04.879 --> 00:40:11.919
It's really cool that your book was built on R Markdown as well. I was wondering,

00:40:11.919 --> 00:40:18.239
what was that process like of writing a book, and how did you decide that you were ready to

00:40:18.239 --> 00:40:25.760
write a book? Two things. One, I'll start off by saying that if it were not for R Markdown,

00:40:25.760 --> 00:40:30.560
there is no way I ever would have written that thing. I can't imagine. Certainly, I'm not going

00:40:30.560 --> 00:40:37.520
to write the entire document in LaTeX. There are people who can, and God bless them. I'm not the

00:40:37.840 --> 00:40:45.360
person that could have that much LaTeX to think about, nor do I want to juggle about

00:40:46.959 --> 00:40:53.520
12 or 13 different Word documents or one monolithic Word document. R Markdown was a

00:40:53.520 --> 00:41:01.679
tremendous solution, and it was really empowering. The idea for the book came about from

00:41:02.479 --> 00:41:09.360
workshops that I and others had been doing for the CAS. We had one-day workshops,

00:41:09.360 --> 00:41:16.959
day-and-a-half workshops. I found that there was a lot of foundational material. I'm thinking about

00:41:18.479 --> 00:41:26.080
vectors and slicing vectors and concatenation and lists and data frames. This was taking up

00:41:26.080 --> 00:41:33.439
a large amount of scarce time. Teach somebody to be an actuary using R in about seven and a

00:41:33.439 --> 00:41:39.600
half hours. That's a tall order. When you spend about three hours or more just making sure that

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:43.120
folks understand what a data frame is, that's scarce time that we're losing.

00:41:44.399 --> 00:41:49.679
Those early slide decks, probably all of which were written in Markdown, by the way. I'm

00:41:49.679 --> 00:41:55.679
translating it to RevealJS or something like that. We already had all of the script for those.

00:41:56.800 --> 00:42:03.919
I sat down with those decks and said, okay, these look like book chapters. You take a 45-minute

00:42:03.919 --> 00:42:09.760
session, and you've already got a lot of the code and the examples. At the time, I thought,

00:42:09.760 --> 00:42:13.439
well, I'll just flesh this out with a few paragraphs, and bang, I'll have a book.

00:42:14.080 --> 00:42:21.679
It wound up being more complicated than that. It turns out that it does take a little bit of time

00:42:21.679 --> 00:42:27.280
to write all of the words in such a way that they make sense. But at that point, it was too late. I

00:42:27.280 --> 00:42:34.239
was already, I think, 80 pages into it and just needed to finish. That's the story about how

00:42:34.239 --> 00:42:43.040
that got started. We started with some more Markdown files. The need for it is to

00:42:43.040 --> 00:42:46.879
give folks some foundational knowledge and just kind of grew from there.

00:42:49.679 --> 00:42:57.600
Awesome. Thank you. One other anonymous question that came in, and thank you to the team gathering

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:02.959
those for me in the background, was how do you share your work currently, especially when teams

00:43:02.959 --> 00:43:10.879
don't have R and need to upload CSV files? I don't have a real strong need to do that.

00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:15.840
My sharing use case is probably not going to resemble yours,

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:21.439
because I'm guessing that the question comes from some points of friction. What I've done

00:43:23.919 --> 00:43:32.239
is, I'm going to say SharePoints, grad school projects. I'm near the end of a master's degree,

00:43:32.239 --> 00:43:38.320
and so I have had some grad school projects. It's Google Drive. The kids, they love Google,

00:43:38.320 --> 00:43:45.199
whereas the older corporate people like SharePoint, they're both fine. That's what I

00:43:45.199 --> 00:43:51.919
use to share data, like that CSV files. What I love to do is to collaborate on GitHub, because

00:43:51.919 --> 00:44:01.919
it is controlled. It feels safe and deliberate. There are obviously some frictional points there

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:08.719
as well. Beyond that, I'm curious what other folks use, if there is some interesting magic

00:44:08.719 --> 00:44:17.360
bullet out there. Yeah. Any thoughts? Feel free to just unmute. I can watch or raise your hand here.

00:44:18.800 --> 00:44:25.840
I know one way that came up previously in a Hangout was creating a Shiny application

00:44:25.840 --> 00:44:32.479
where people who didn't use R could upload the dataset and work with it in the app.

00:44:33.679 --> 00:44:36.879
Any other ideas, feel free to share in the chat too.

